51. What is a JOIN?
Definition

A JOIN is used to combine rows from two or more tables based on a related column.

Usually, tables are joined using a Primary Key and a Foreign Key.

Types of Joins
INNER JOIN
LEFT JOIN
RIGHT JOIN
FULL JOIN
SELF JOIN
CROSS JOIN
Syntax
SELECT columns
FROM table1
JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
INNER JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
52. INNER JOIN
Definition

An INNER JOIN returns only the matching rows from both tables.

Rows without matching values are ignored.

Syntax
SELECT columns
FROM table1
INNER JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
INNER JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
Output
Name	Department
Rahul	IT
Priya	HR

Explanation

Aman is excluded because DeptID = 3 doesn't exist.
Neha is excluded because DeptID is NULL.
53. LEFT JOIN
Definition

A LEFT JOIN returns:

All rows from the left table
Matching rows from the right table
If no match exists, NULL values are returned.
Syntax
SELECT columns
FROM table1
LEFT JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
LEFT JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
Output
Name	Department
Rahul	IT
Priya	HR
Aman	NULL
Neha	NULL
54. RIGHT JOIN
Definition

A RIGHT JOIN returns:

All rows from the right table
Matching rows from the left table
If no match exists, NULL values are returned.
Syntax
SELECT columns
FROM table1
RIGHT JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
RIGHT JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
Output
Name	Department
Rahul	IT
Priya	HR
NULL	Sales

Sales exists in Departments but has no employee.

55. FULL JOIN (FULL OUTER JOIN)
Definition

A FULL JOIN returns:

All matching rows
All rows from the left table
All rows from the right table

Unmatched values are filled with NULL.

Note: MySQL does not support FULL OUTER JOIN directly. It can be simulated using LEFT JOIN UNION RIGHT JOIN.

Syntax
SELECT columns
FROM table1
FULL OUTER JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
Output
Name	Department
Rahul	IT
Priya	HR
Aman	NULL
Neha	NULL
NULL	Sales
56. SELF JOIN
Definition

A SELF JOIN joins a table with itself.

It is useful when comparing rows within the same table, such as employees and their managers.

Example Table
EmpID	Name	ManagerID
101	Rahul	103
102	Priya	103
103	Aman	NULL
Syntax
SELECT A.Name AS Employee,
B.Name AS Manager
FROM Employee A
JOIN Employee B
ON A.ManagerID = B.EmpID;
Output
Employee	Manager
Rahul	Aman
Priya	Aman
57. CROSS JOIN
Definition

A CROSS JOIN returns the Cartesian Product of two tables.

Every row from the first table is combined with every row from the second table.

If:

Table A has 3 rows
Table B has 4 rows

Result = 3 × 4 = 12 rows

Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table1
CROSS JOIN table2;
Example
Table A
Color
Red
Blue
Table B
Size
S
M
SELECT *
FROM Colors
CROSS JOIN Sizes;
Output
Color	Size
Red	S
Red	M
Blue	S
Blue	M
58. JOIN vs Subquery
Definition
JOIN

Combines data from multiple tables into a single result set.

Subquery

A query written inside another query.

Comparison
JOIN	Subquery
Combines tables	Nested query
Usually faster	Can be slower for large datasets
Better for related tables	Useful for filtering or calculations
Easy to read with aliases	Can become difficult when nested deeply
JOIN Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
Subquery Example
SELECT Name
FROM Employees
WHERE DeptID IN
(
SELECT DeptID
FROM Departments
WHERE Department='IT'
);
59. Join Conditions
Definition

A join condition specifies how two tables are related.

It is written using the ON clause.

Without a proper join condition, SQL may return incorrect results.

Syntax
SELECT *
FROM table1
JOIN table2
ON table1.column = table2.column;
Example
SELECT Employees.Name,
Departments.Department
FROM Employees
JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;

Here,

Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID

is the join condition.

60. Common Join Mistakes
1. Forgetting the ON Clause

❌ Wrong

SELECT *
FROM Employees
JOIN Departments;

This may produce a Cartesian product or a syntax error depending on the database.

2. Joining on the Wrong Column

❌ Wrong

ON Employees.EmpID = Departments.DeptID

✔ Correct

ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID
3. Using the Wrong Join Type

Using an INNER JOIN when a LEFT JOIN is required may cause missing rows in the result.

4. Duplicate Rows

Joining tables with duplicate matching values can return more rows than expected.

5. Ambiguous Column Names

When both tables have the same column name (e.g., DeptID), always prefix the table name or alias.

❌ Wrong

SELECT DeptID
FROM Employees
JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;

✔ Correct

SELECT Employees.DeptID
FROM Employees
JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;
6. Forgetting Table Aliases in Complex Joins

Instead of

SELECT Employees.Name
FROM Employees
INNER JOIN Departments
ON Employees.DeptID = Departments.DeptID;

Use aliases for readability:

SELECT E.Name,
D.Department
FROM Employees E
INNER JOIN Departments D
ON E.DeptID = D.DeptID;
Summary of SQL Joins
Join Type	Returns
INNER JOIN	Only matching rows from both tables
LEFT JOIN	All rows from the left table + matching rows from the right
RIGHT JOIN	All rows from the right table + matching rows from the left
FULL JOIN	All rows from both tables, matching where possible
SELF JOIN	A table joined with itself
CROSS JOIN	Every row from the first table combined with every row from the second
